    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>Gay Marriage And the Campaign</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Nathaniel Frank comments on Gary Bauer's Oct 8 Op-Ed expressing opposition to same-sex marriage and criticizing Dick Cheney's tolerance of such relationships</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>In his opposition to same-sex marriage (''Fuzzy Morality,'' Op-Ed, Oct. 8), Gary Bauer borrows the rhetoric of the founding fathers to suggest that Americans should be ''tempering our liberty with virtue.'' He criticizes the vice-presidential candidates' call, as Dick Cheney put it, to ''tolerate and accommodate whatever kind of relationships people want to enter into.''</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>In his opposition to same-sex marriage (''Fuzzy Morality,'' Op-Ed, Oct. 8), Gary Bauer borrows the rhetoric of the founding fathers to suggest that Americans should be ''tempering our liberty with virtue.'' He criticizes the vice-presidential candidates' call, as Dick Cheney put it, to ''tolerate and accommodate whatever kind of relationships people want to enter into.''</p>
        <p>Mr. Bauer says ''the last 30 years have been a social disaster largely because people have felt free to enter into -- or leave -- any relationship they wanted.'' Yet gays are not asking for unbridled freedom, but for the same civic freedoms that other Americans enjoy to celebrate and sanction a loving commitment between two people. We are asking, in another of Mr. Bauer's borrowed phrases, for our country to ''insure a place at the table for all'' its citizens.</p>
        <p>NATHANIEL FRANK  Brooklyn, Oct. 8, 2000</p>
      </block>
